<br>
I'm not going to go into details on why each fight is so different, but I think if you really believe your only job is to keep max melee range, then you don't understand the encounters and don't play your class well.  Do most encounters require cheal? yes.  Do most encounters require attacking a mob? yes.  That's the nature of the game.<br>
<br>
There is a difference between being ok at eq and being really good at eq.  There's quite a bit you can do in this game to have a major impact on fights.  Many people fall into the &quot;hit a and afk&quot; mentality.  This doesn't mean that it's the game's fault, it means that the player is not very good.<br>
<br>
Try a cheal chain and tell me again it's easy.  It's not.  The first time I tried a cheal chain myself we lost the fight cause I fucked up.  Now I chain fairly regularly and consider myself good at it, but it took practice, and it's the most intense thing I have yet done in eq.  It's not easy at all.<br>
<br>
I've wiped MANY times because clerics fuck up the cheal chain, sometimes horribly.  If it's so easy, why do tanks ever die?  If you work it out, most chains are tight enough so that the main tank should never die, if executed correctly.  If you really believe a cheal chain is a simple thing, then you are effectively calling a substantial portion of your guild morons.<br>
<br>
I really don't think eq is the game for you.  Most of us spend our time talking about how we could tweak eq to make it a bit better here or there, all the while understanding that it's an amazing game, the best we've ever played.  You want to turn an apple into a pineapple.  Why not just buy a pineapple instead?<br>
