<br>
I'll start off by saying that compared to the top-end gameplay of action oriented games like Quake, nothing in EQ that I've witnessed requires very much skill.  Most of what does currently require traditional gaming skills in EQ is found in PVP play or in EQ's past, when the game was younger and tougher.<br>
<br>
When I say that cheal chains require skill, I'm speaking subjectively within the context of EQ.<br>
<br>
There is not a lot of skill required to merely do a cheal chain.  However, with the chains that I've seen, and the chains that I've been part of, there is a lot of room for an individual to do his/her job well and for the clerics to work off of each other and coordinate as a team.<br>
<br>
I believe that a big difference between a guild who can do mobs with a minimal amount of resources and a guild that needs to zerg is smart, efficient healing.<br>
<br>
Because of the nature of cheal, it does require more timing and thought than any other heal.<br>
<br>
Would SOE do heals differently if they had an opportunity?  Of course.  They would redo countless elements of the game differently.  They never envisioned Cheal as a battle spell and don't like it.  This is true of much of the game such as FD pulling, camps, etc..  The players have really defined EQ gameplay, and I always felt that this pissed the hell out of Brad.<br>
<br>
But, players making use of available tools tools in unconventional ways helps make EQ fun.  If people did everything the way Brad had intended, the game would be very boring.  Tactics are fun, and people not only enjoy coming up with them, but implementing them.<br>
<br>
As for character advancement, well, I liked to use all of my available heal lines.  I always understood that cheal was self-scaling, and was effectively upgraded with each expansion. A more varried top-line heal would not have made the class any more enjoyable, and certainly wouldn't have the epic feel of cheal.  Clerics don't have the advancement enjoyments of other classes, but I think that comes with role specialization in EQ.  Clerics envy Druids for diversity, Druids envy clerics for specialization.  Shrug.<br>
<br>
The balance of the entire game is out of whack.  To blame cheal for that is wrong, to single out cheal is pointless.  Cheal chains weren't necessary and weren't really used until mobs with massive HP's in SOV, and AC obviously was going to be capped in SOV whether players came up with cheal chains or not.  Much of EQ has evolved past its original design documented, and much in EQ has reached caps of some sort at some point. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#dcdeed><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub41.ezboard.com/ucerosofvazaelle.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Ceros of Vazaelle</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Senior Member</span><br>  Posts: 886<br> <font color=#FFFFFF>(8/10/02 9:41:18 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub41.ezboard.com/fvazaellecommunitycenterfrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=3124.topic&index=65>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: ...</span><hr size=1> Tenken,<br>
